abstract: Western and Ukrainian officials have said Moscow’s stockpile of missiles was dwindling. But the assaults this week raise questions about that.
snippet: Western and Ukrainian officials have said Moscow’s stockpile of missiles was dwindling. But the assaults this week raise questions about that.
lead_paragraph: The 96-missile barrage fired across Ukraine on Tuesday was Russia’s biggest aerial attack of the war so far. But it followed months of assertions by Western and Ukrainian officials that Moscow’s stockpile of missiles and other weapons was rapidly dwindling.

main: How Was Russia Able to Launch Its Biggest Aerial Attack on Ukraine?
print_headline: After Russia’s Biggest Aerial Attack, Questions Emerge About Its Missile Stockpile

abstract: Cats have a reputation for being aloof, but a new study has found that their relationships with their owners may be stronger than we thought.
snippet: Cats have a reputation for being aloof, but a new study has found that their relationships with their owners may be stronger than we thought.
lead_paragraph: Every cat owner has a story to tell of being blanked by their cat: We call to our cat, it turns away, and some of us might be left wondering why we didn’t get a dog. But your cat may be listening after all. More than that, it cares more than you may think.

main: Your Cat Might Not Be Ignoring You When You Speak
print_headline: Finicky Listeners: Does Your Cat Always Ignore You? Maybe It Just Looks That Way.

abstract: Some researchers claim that chatbots have developed theory of mind. But is that just our own theory of mind gone wild?
snippet: Some researchers claim that chatbots have developed theory of mind. But is that just our own theory of mind gone wild?
lead_paragraph: Mind reading is common among us humans. Not in the ways that psychics claim to do it, by gaining access to the warm streams of consciousness that fill every individual’s experience, or in the ways that mentalists claim to do it, by pulling a thought out of your head at will. Everyday mind reading is more subtle: We take in people’s faces and movements, listen to their words and then decide or intuit what might be going on in their heads.

main: Can a Machine Know That We Know What It Knows?
print_headline: Human Power to Process Cues May Be Next Frontier for Bots

main: Concern Grows in Israel’s Military as Netanyahu Nears Coalition Deal
print_headline: In a Rare Letter, Israel Warns Soldiers to Stay Out of Politics

abstract: For better or worse, Jay Gould revolutionized the world of finance in the 19th century. In “American Rascal,” Greg Steinmetz tells his story.
snippet: For better or worse, Jay Gould revolutionized the world of finance in the 19th century. In “American Rascal,” Greg Steinmetz tells his story.
lead_paragraph: On April 5, 1882, Theodore Roosevelt stood in the New York State Assembly and demanded an investigation. The indignant 23-year-old accused a clique of “swindlers,” “wealthy stock gamblers,” “men whose financial dishonesty is a matter of common notoriety,” of corruptly monopolizing New York City’s elevated railroads. The plot’s mastermind, he implied, was Jay Gould.

main: The Robber Baron Who Remade Wall Street in His Own Image

abstract: DeepMind has expanded its database of microscopic biological mechanisms, hoping to accelerate research into all living things.

abstract: Ukraine is feeling short-term pressure from its Western backers for success in a looming counteroffensive. Vladimir Putin seems to be operating on a longer timeline.
